<p>For almost 1700 years, <strong>the city remained hidden and was slowly forgotten</strong> and erased from history, until in 1748 a group of explorers rediscovered the site, and much to their surprise, underneath a thick layer of dust and debris, the city of Pompeii was mostly intact! Now the formerly forgotten city of Pompeii offers an accurate picture of life in a prosperous Roman town 2,000 years ago. Homes, bathhouses, food stores, furnishings, bronze statues, and mosaics can all be seen – along with the plaster casts of victims. Pompeii is now an open-air museum of extraordinary charm, and <a href="http://www.solede.com/rome/naples--pompeii-day-tour/?utm_source=blog&utm_medium=articolo%20blog&utm_campaign=The%20Roman%20Pompeii%3A%20a%20layer%20of%20ash%20to%20hush%20a%20city">can be visited daily with our tours</a></p>